;We should all be able to choose – with clarity and confidence – what information we share with what companies, understanding the tradeoffs we’re making when we do.
Yessefk ad nizmir ad nefren s wudem ibanen, di laman anwa isefka ara nebḍu neɣ anta tikebbaniwin ara yawin isefka-agi, s tmusni ɣef ayen i nettmuddu ticki neqbel.


;Right now, we all lack meaningful choice online – privacy policies are often miles long and hard to read, we don’t understand what information we’re sharing or when, and opting out is seldom on the menu.
Ass-a, srid, yewɛer ad tferneḍ abrid ibanen – tisertiyin n tbaḍnit ɣezzif-it udiɣ ẓẓay-it akken ad ten-tegzud, ur negzi ara anwa isefka i nbeṭṭu neɣ melmi ad ten-nebdu neɣ allalen yellan akken ticki nebɣa ad nsefsex beṭṭu-agi n isefka.


;91% of adults agree that consumers have lost control of how personal information is collected and used by companies.
91 % n yemdanen ttwalin d akken imsudar ur ẓrin ara amek ttwaleqḍen isefka-nsen neɣ amek tikebbaniyin seqdacent isefka-agi ibeṭṭun yemdanen.


