;Government Surveillance: Keeping prying eyes and ears out of your business
Aqaṛeɛ anabaḍan: Ḥrez iman-ik seg yir allen d yir imezzuɣen


;We should all have the freedom to be ourselves — online and off – without surveillance, judgment and imposed societal bias.
Yessefk meṛṛa ad nili d ilelliyen, ad yili uzref ad nili d nekni kan, ama sridneɣ ala, s war ma iqurɛeɣ unabaḍ, neɣ aɣ-yedfeṛ yir wawal di tmetti.


;You wouldn’t want the government following your every move in real life – there’s no reason they should be shadowing you on the Internet. The Edward Snowden disclosures showed that even democracies can and do take liberties with your privacy.
Ur tqebbled ara akken anabad ad k-yeṭṭafaṛ deg yal asurif, neɣ kra n wayen ara tegged di tmeddurt inek n yal ass, ihi ur issefk ara ad xedmen aya di ula di Internet. Awal i d-yebra Edward Snowden yemmal-d d akken ula d inabaden imagdayen ɛefsen ɣef kra n izerfan icudden ɣer tudert tusligt.


;Just four in 10 (38%) of internet users trust that their activities on the internet are not being monitored.
Ala kuẓ n iseqdacen n internet ɣef 10 (38 %) i yumnen d akken leqdic-nsen d internet ur ittwaqareɛ ara.


